When I was growing up we had a toaster. Or, for accuracy, I should say when I was 
\f1\i born
\f0\i0 , we had a toaster. Around the point when I learned to ride a bicycle the handle fell off. It was taped back on with duck tape.  I hated that toaster. The dials were confusing and the white plastic stained a nicotine-addict yellow. When I was 10 the toaster got very hot one day and belched up a plume of black smoke, staining the wall behind it. \
\
 I thought surely that would be the end of it. But instead, the wretched toaster was gently fixed and placed right back next to the gleaming microwave. It sat there, underneath the scar it had left for another 8 years.\
\
I never understood it. Or my parents strange obstinacy in keeping a device that 
\f1\i worked
\f2\i0  but could not be said to 
\i work well
\i0  and was, in my opinion, an eyesore in an otherwise pretty kitchen. I asked if it was the money, if the reason we had to have this stupid semi-broken toaster was that we could not afford a new one.\
\
 I was told that no, we could, if we wanted, afford a new toaster. It wasn\'92t about that. It was that you don\'92t throw out things that work. They may take a little more energy, they may break more frequently and have to be nursed back to health\'97but an object is like a relationship. When you find something good, you don\'92t just ditch it for the next shiny thing. \
\
It was the same way my Dad\'92s wheezing station wagon (mark two) was retired only when it was hit by a Prius going forty onto a local onramp.\
 \
It is the same way with my Dad\'92s current ancient station wagon (mark three) which is nearing the twenty year mark and leaks when it rains. Sometimes, on twilight evenings, I catch my Dad wistfully reminicising over the original station wagon, the one that took him up and down between Florida and upstate New York when my parents went to separate grad schools. That ancient station wagon (mark one) was sacrificed when they bought one way tickets out to California thirty years ago, but never forgotten. \
\

\f0 It took building a life of my own, before I started to finally realize what my parents were trying to teach me. The value of money and the resistance inherent in the 
\f1\i good enough
