\f0 Our current consumer culture churns out goods manufactured far away from our eyes with costs uncalculated by us as we stand in line at the local Target. To keep the apparatus churning, requires two things: 1. the ability to continually produce new, marginally different, marginally more powerful merchandise at a very low cost 2. To convince the consumer that our relationships with the things that we have do not exist and are not meaningful. It\'92s perhaps strange, but right now, I find the act of 
\f1\i ownership
\f2\i0  a slightly radical act\'97because the world is hell bent on convincing me that nothing is 
\i truly mine
\i0 \'97not a car which I can lease, a laptop which I can borrow, an apartment I can rent, a large phone which I can trade in in two years for something gargantuan. Because the flip side of \'93possession\'94 or perhaps \'93partnership\'94 is responsibility. We take care of things that are ours. We cultivate them. We don\'92t throw them away for something shinier. 
